<TITLE> BCB preparing for legal battle </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 2 (bdnews24.com)  The Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) is preparing a response to the legal notice served on it by three Premier League clubs over holding the relegation matches of the last edition of the league. "We have got the legal notice of three clubs and sent it over to the lawyer, who is considering necessary steps," said Ahmed Saiiadul Alam, chairman of the media committee of the BCB. Brothers Union, Indira Road KC and City Club Monday served a legal notice on the BCB, asking it to explain why its had moved to hold the relegation matches of the Premier League seventh months into its conclusion. The BCB has decided to hold the relegation matches among three bottom-placed teams in the 12-team point-table on October 4-7. Two teams will be relegated to the First Division League from the Premier League, but the three clubs refused to play the matches. Alam said the BCB was preparing to go ahead with the matches despite the legal notice. "We have not changed our mind yet on holding the matches. The umpires will take field in time. If the clubs don't turn up, action will be taken in line with rules," added Alam. bdn
